2	 * The Clockworks — event substrate and standing-order engine (Pillar 5).
3	 *
4	 * The factory:
5	 *
6	 *   - Declares plugin id `clockworks` (derived from the package name).
7	 *   - Requires the Stacks and Clerk; consumes the `relays` and
8	 *     `events` kit vocabularies.
9	 *   - Publishes two books (`events`, `event_dispatches`) under owner id
10	 *     `clockworks`, with the index set anticipated by the runner /
11	 *     status query patterns in `docs/architecture/clockworks.md`.
12	 *   - Resolves the Stacks during `start()` and obtains writable handles
13	 *     on both books so `emit()`, `processEvents()`, and the future
14	 *     daemon can use them without re-resolving Stacks.
15	 *   - Provides the `ClockworksApi` (`emit()`, `validateSignal()`,
16	 *     `resolveRelay()`, `processEvents()`) that downstream tasks extend.
17	 *   - Builds a name-keyed relay registry from `ctx.kits('relays')`
18	 *     entries merged with the apparatus's own `supportKit.relays`. The
19	 *     registry is closure-scoped, cleared at the top of every `start()`
20	 *     for idempotent restart semantics, and uses first-writer-wins on
21	 *     duplicate names with a lattice-format warning. Reachable from the
22	 *     api via `resolveRelay(name)`.
23	 *   - Builds a merged event set from `ctx.kits('events')` contributions
24	 *     plus `guild.json clockworks.events`. The plugin layer is start-
25	 *     scoped (built once); the operator layer is re-read per call to
26	 *     `validateSignal` so hot-edits land without restart. The four
27	 *     fail-loud boot guards — plugin-vs-plugin name collision, function-
28	 *     form throw or non-object return, malformed kit value, malformed
29	 *     guild.json value — surface at apparatus boot time.
30	 *   - Exposes `processEvents()` — the event-triggered dispatch entry
31	 *     point. Each call re-reads `clockworks.standingOrders` from
32	 *     `guild.json`, validates them via the standing-order validator,
33	 *     and delegates to the pure `runDispatchSweep` primitive in
34	 *     `dispatcher.ts`. The CLI (later commission) and daemon (later
35	 *     commission) compose on top of the same primitive.
36	 *
37	 * `start()` primes the book handles, the registry, and the dispatch
38	 * path; `stop()` is currently a no-op — Arbor's
39	 * `StartedGuild.shutdown()` invokes it during reverse-topo teardown
40	 * (the apparatus has no in-flight handles of its own to release; the
41	 * Clockworks daemon's poll loop is owned by `runForegroundDaemon`,
